He hasn't done a very good job of that. So he has opened himself up to that and they're the ones who stepped in to try and score political points, which is what do you in an election.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: Jesse, I think this is mostly an unfair attack on Biden. Do you agree with me?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oh, poor Joe. Let's be nice to the frontrunner. He's so fragile. It doesn't sound confident the Democrats are whispering about letting Joe skate by. I think in -- what was it, 2008, Obama attacked the frontrunner Hillary, beat her, and won the general. Donald Trump attack Jeb the frontrunner of the primary, end up winning the general. So you want a competitive primary because you want the eventual nominee to come out battle-tested. Remember last time, I think, Bernie said, oh, I don't care about Hillary's emails.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: The damn emails.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: The damn emails. No one cares. That was dumb. It hurt Bernie, but it ultimately hurt Hillary, because Hillary still towards the end could not defend her emails effectively because she wasn't forced to formulate a strategy. If you look at Biden right now, he's so ripe for a takedown. He's so vulnerable. And his jaw --he's got a glass jaw. To now be whining and try to start strategizing this early before the first debate crying mercy?

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: I guess you're not too sympathetic.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It looks so much so weak, Doug.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: Emily, are you all sympathetic to Biden?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: No, I'm not. I think this --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Welcome to The Five.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: I got it.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: I think it speaks volume about the establishment and what they're trying to do. We saw this in 2016, right, when they basically said, look, leave Hillary alone. Joe is their establishment candidate. But I think the difference is that in 2016, Hillary had that air of inevitability and Biden doesn't have that.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: And clearly, these other candidates don't think that he has and don't care, they're not interested in the V.P. situation. They're not worried about their careers if he picks a cabinet because they don't think it's going to come to that. And I think the ones that are clearly kind of toeing the line might argue later, oh, I was help pushing you -- I was pushing you on an issue that's important to the base, but otherwise, it's clear that no one else thinks that he's the inevitable frontrunner, except for, by the way, Trump's pollster, Tony Fabricio, who says he believes it's going to be Elizabeth Warren.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: I think there's a good shot -- there could be one. Greg, do you think he's going to get taken --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: -- down?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: But I will meet you in the sympathetic world briefly --

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: Thank you.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- because Joe was trying to make a point that he could work with anyone and, ironically, he was talking about Democrats who now don't want to work with him. So it's kind of a rich, full circle like that movie the Lion King?

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: Oh, the circle of life, Greg.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, thank you. I -- OK. So I feel bad --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. I feel bad for Joe until I remember that he has pulled the very same crap on Republicans repeatedly. The smear machine created by the left is that crocodile that will ultimately eat everybody, and you think you'll be safe but it will eat you too. I mean, remember, he was the one who've said that Trump didn't condemn white supremacy when he did. He also said Romney was going to put you all back in chains. So he's smeared people who essentially voted for Trump. He's made his bed with the smear machine and, unfortunately, he's got to lie in that bed.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's why he's so sleepy.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You walked right into it.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: If you want to reach out and show that you can work with the other side, then talk about John McCain and Mike Pence.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: You see, that's the point. As a Democrat, that's where I think this needed to go, and he blew it by talking about Eastland and --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Because he talked about him before a lot.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: I know that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I mean, he did Strom Thurmond's eulogy, right?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: He's been telling the same story for years and it all caught up with him.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah. And now he's -- he's now in a new world where it doesn't matter.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: Up next, new drama in the Jussie Smollett case. And Dominican officials down play the wave of mysterious deaths.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: That's right. Major developments in the Jussie Smollett saga, it continues. A Cook County Illinois judge is appointing a special prosecutor to investigate the handling of the case by Chicago's top prosecutor Kim Foxx, as you remember her office dropped all charges against the actor. It was a big surprise. He was accused of staging a hate crime attack on himself. It's tough to do. The judge saying that Foxx did not have the right to assign her top deputy to lead the case after she colloquially recused herself. In a statement Foxx said that she disagrees with the judge's decision. So, Emily, this is really fascinating because I -- you know, you're a lawyer, you can explain this better. But I was wondering if there was some double jeopardy in here, but the special prosecutor said that no, they can reopen the case and Jussie Smollett can be charged once again with all 16 counts of fewer or even more.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Yes, and anyone else that has been caught up in this can be charged as well. I want to point out for viewers a couple things. Number one, the judge, Judge Toomin came out swinging at Kim Foxx. He said essentially that her -- the phrase she used, the acting states attorney, (INAUDIBLE), basically was made up in her imagination and, therefore, this is the important part, the arrest, the subsequent prosecution and the dropping of all charges, therefore, is inexplicable. It's like wiping the slate clean. It's all moot. And that's why it restores the entire situation back to that original place. Secondly, there's a whole host of concurrent investigations happening. And here, the defense was arguing, well, look, we're duplicating the efforts of the inspector general. Judge Toomin obviously said, no, you're not. So right now for viewers, we have the inspector general. We have now a special prosecutor. We have the FBI investigating the hoax. We have the city of Chicago lawsuit against Jussie for costs. And then don't forget the brothers who have sued his attorneys. Final point, she blamed her ethics -- yes, she blamed her ethics officer on it. And remember, she ran on that platform of I'm going to instill an ethics officer and bring ethics back to the city of Chicago. She failed.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: Other than the fact that this is a high profile actor and the whole case is weird, we're still really fascinated --

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: We are.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: -- with it.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: We are. And, you know, notwithstanding, Emily, what you say, Jessie Smollett --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Jussie. Jussie.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: Jussie, sorry.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: Is not -- they are not going to ignore or drop the double jeopardy argument. So this case is going to take a while if it ever comes to trial. And there will be substantial arguments that it is double jeopardy, and my hunch is we might get a plea out of this for a very modest offense.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: I mean, the way he was talking about it. He felt like he was scot-free.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: And, you know, he was -- I'm my mother's son, and everyone knows that I would never do anything like this. The real attackers are out there.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right. And this is why Americans think that the whole system is rigged because Michelle Obama's former chief of staff makes the call to Foxx, then he gets a sweetheart deal. Comey gives Hillary a sweetheart deal. Hillary rigs the primary against Bernie. Mueller stacks him team with 19 Democrats. Celebrities are paying cash bribes to get their kids into school. Sneaky Snipes is messing around with the vote count. It's all bogus if you're a regular American who is working hard, you feel like if you're not someone who is politically connected or rich, you can't really work the system in your favor. So that's why people are obsessed with the story and they want to see Jussie pay a price.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: Yeah, because Lori Loughlin is not going to prison.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No. I think Jesse just came up with his book proposal. You just did your table of contents. I have to hand it to Smollett in the sense that he didn't just sink his own career, he sank the show Empire, right? And he's -- I think he's destroying Kim Foxx's career too. He's like that paint canister that bank tellers slip into the money bag to give to the bank robbers, and they're almost there and the whole thing just explodes and they're covered in paint. My solution for him, and I've said this before, is that he should come clean and meet with the people that he smeared. He smeared these imaginary MAGA supporters. If he actually did a meet with actual Trump supporters, that could go towards a certain path of forgiveness.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: Well, speaking of forgiveness, it doesn't seems like we've got a lot right now for the Dominican Republic. We've been following this story the D.R. tourism minister calling the rash of suspicious deaths of Americans, quote, exaggerated at a news conference earlier. This is Fox News confirms two more Americans have died during recent vacations in recent years there. The daughter of one of them slamming the Dominican official. Watch this.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: I don't understand how somebody can see what you is this 11 deaths now. They all have somewhat of the same cause. They're all in the same area. He's claiming that, you know, this can happen anywhere. And I completely agree heart attacks can happen anywhere, bad things can happen anywhere, but where else are we seeing 11 cases of almost the same thing in the same area, it's the Dominican.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: Jeff Paul is in Santa Domingo with the latest, Jeff?

utterances.speaker: JEFF PAUL, CORRESPONDENT
utterances.utterance: Yeah, Kennedy, we were in that room as that tourism minister tried to explain what was going on to a room packed full of local and international journalists where he basically summed this up, again, as an exaggeration saying that most of the situation has been fueled by speculation. He also says that the Dominican Republic has nothing to hide, and that it was the D.R. who reached out to the FBI to help in this situation. The major concern for them at the moment at least one of them is the tourism, that's the lifeblood for this Caribbean island. But we did at one point, get a chance to ask his Minister of Tourism what he would say to the families of those 11 tourists who have died in the span of 12, the past 12 months from June of last year to June of this year. He says, while he is sympathetic to those families who have lost the loved ones, he continues to hammer down the fact that he does not believe there is any sort of mystery surrounding the deaths. And the big thing that we are all waiting for and it seems like this entire island and people watching this story waiting for the results of these toxicology tests of three of the Americans who have died, these are the tests that the FBI is involved and assisting with. We might not get those results until next month. Kennedy.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: All right, Jeff. Thanks so much. Greg, I want to start with you, because they have been - a lot of these families have been pressured to cremate their loved ones.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: And the government has not administered toxicology tests majority of these victims.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That is infuriating. I watched the interview with that young woman and about the fact that they were just saying, the toxicology will be on the death certificate. Can we just - can you just sign this here, so we can get rid of the body. I mean it is pretty outrageous. The problem right now is the DR has kind of a point about speculation, because it's - we're in this fog of media blather and I include myself in that. I don't know what's going on. I think the most obvious thing is it was a bad batch of cheap booze that was sold to these places--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Or espionage.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Jesse's got the espionage tip, you go.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, first of all, I feel terrible for Jeff who drew that assignment in the DR I mean he might be stuck down there for weeks if this story keeps up. I'd like to take a look at that expense report when he gets back. It was disappointed today to find out that my own handyman has violated my travel ban. He was fixing my sink today and he told me he's going to the DR with 18 people and totally ignored all my warnings. He did say, he was going to do one thing. He said, he's buying all the booze at the duty-free place.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That was my suggestion.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Stock up that and not touch the minibar. So, I'm glad he's heeding some of our warnings.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: I was invited a couple of weeks ago for a business trip to go to the DR I said, thanks but no thanks and I have friends of mine similarly who are go and come hell or high water.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Like Bob Menendez.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: Well, the Dominican Republic has to do something because the perception is that this is a deadly place to take a vacation. And people who have their tourist dollars to spend might just go spend them somewhere else.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: That's why it was so surprising that the Minister of Tourism is saying unequivocally there are no mysterious deaths. He should get a couple inches and say, we are working on it, we will get back to you, our condolences. And then we have a little bit more credibility, we can extend to them. Second point though it's not just about the booze, because these toxins might have been inhaled or topical or ingested so.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: And that can't be ruled out.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Exactly.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: No, but the FBI will do much more work on this. But it's a shame for the families who have no--

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: Great tragedy.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: Recall at this point. All right. The Fastest Seven is coming up next, featuring a crazy fight at an airport, a costly divorce and the comfort foods of the Democrat candidates. Don't go anywhere.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Welcome back. Time for the Fastest Seven. First up, a terrifying incident at an airport in Phoenix caught on tape. Surveillance footage released there showing a 19-year-old man rushing through metal detectors and brawling with a group of TSA agents before 10 AM by the way, sending one agent to the hospital and four others into urgent care. They've all since been released and he was subdued and has since been arrested on assault charges. His bail was just $1500, Greg.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That seems highly personal. Like something when - there's more to this story. Something happened. I don't know what it is, but you know it's a tough job. Everything about the TSA is gloomy, right. It's gloomy for them and it's gloomy for us like it's like it used to be glamorous to travel and now it's just kind of you see the crowd, the spectacle, the noise and your heart sinks. There has to be a way to improve this. Right.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: And they have one.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: Bring back the Concorde.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: I was talking to a TSA agent last weekend and he said, they're trying to learn certainty and cheerfulness at the same time.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That's good.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: But the certainty being more important.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: And bashful.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I blame Al-Qaeda. You know if it wasn't for the 9/11 attacks, you wouldn't have this ridiculous amount of security where you're having babies being like full body checked and grandmothers being like taken aside. I'm not saying the TSA did something to provoke this, but when you get to the airport and your flight is about to take off and this guy is telling you to take off your shoes again, I'm not justifying the attack, I'm saying, tensions are high, tensions are very high.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: Well, and that's why it's a surprising response from the TSA, because they say they're prepared for an active shooter and do drills, but they're not prepared for unruly passengers who might attack some of their agents and I'm like why wouldn't you be--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Combat.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: The airports and traveling, yes, it's a giant pressure cooker, but also, they say that this young man is mentally disturbed, and you should - in a nervous hospital.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: There you go.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: All right. Up next, they always say that marriage isn't over until it's over. One man in Detroit had to learn that the hard way after being ordered by court to share his $80 million lottery jackpot with his ex-wife. He had bought the winning ticket in 2013 while they were separated, but the divorce wasn't finalized until 2018. Now the winnings were deemed marital property and now he has to pony up $15 million to his ex, isn't love grand. So, Michigan is not a community property state. It's an equitable division state, an equitable distribution state which means that the judges determine what is an equitable distribution and that doesn't mean equal, it means fair. And also, that's why the date of separation doesn't matter like it does in community property states where that stops the economic union clock. Here it's basically a free for all and judges can do what they do.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: My attitude is if you've got $65 million from me, I'm happy to give $15 million--

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: Slow down, Bernie Sanders.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: I'm a free market capitalist. I'm also not a fool.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'm thinking if you know you've left a bad marriage and you're now a millionaire I'm not going to be like worry that much about this guy, probably really happy.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: Yes, I bet he is.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Well, the fact that he defended it in court meant that he wasn't. He tried.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'm sure his dirty lawyers are trying to fight it, so they can get paid. You know how those guys are.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Kennedy, what do you think.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: No, I'm on his side on this one. He bought the ticket. It was his and they had already decided to end their union. So, he should get to keep the scratch and that has to be a tough check for him to write.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know what, I'm going to go to the person whose wisdom always comes first in my mind, Geraldo.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I knew you were going to say that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Geraldo's advice on a divorce, give them everything they want.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And that's why he's still working.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, that's right. That's what it is. He always says, give them everything. It's going to hurt, but it won't hurt as bad as if you don't give them everything they want. And I love lotteries. It's a voluntary tax. I wish everything - I wish we had 100 times more lotteries.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Except the Visa lottery.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Did anybody see the other case that was embedded in there, the quick check where he bought the lottery ticket is where he had proposed to the ex-wife that then got the money.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Wow.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: This is so--

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: How romantic.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: All right. So finally, The New York Times asked the 2020 candidates what their favorite comfort food was on the campaign trail. Some of the answers are just downright perplexing.

utterances.speaker: SEN. CORY BOOKER, D-N.J., PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: But when you're vegan that means lots of veggies on the go.

utterances.speaker: REP. TULSI GABBARD, D-HI, PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: I try to stay away from it, but Vegan Cupcakes.

utterances.speaker: MARIANNE WILLIAMSON, D-PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: I have no comfort food.

utterances.speaker: PETE BUTTIGIEG, D-IND., PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: The word got out that I like beef jerky.

utterances.speaker: REP. ERIC SWALWELL, D-CALIF., PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: It's really comfort coffee.

utterances.speaker: REP. KIRSTEN GILLIBRAND, D-N.Y., PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: Glass of whiskey at the end of the night.

utterances.speaker: SEN. ELIZABETH WARREN, D-MASS., PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: Probably chips and guacamole.

utterances.speaker: SEN. KAMALA HARRIS, D-CALIF., PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: French fries.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: All right.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: Funny.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Yes. What do you guys think?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Can I just say that this is a window into the soul of a phony. Because if you try to virtue signal when the question is asking you about a vice.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You're a complete fake. Oh, you know I try to stay away from performing charity. That's my comfort food is, I perform charity.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: Eating cupcakes, come on.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: What happened to steaks and French fries.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: Kirsten Gillibrand, she would like - if not.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Best thing she's ever said.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: I appreciate Tim Ryan.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: Don't worry, it's only one glass.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: Tim Ryan said, I'm an ice cream guy. I don't know why Kamala Harris thought that was funny, but French fries.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That was weird.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: French fries were hilarious.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: Veggies and beef jerky like words got mouth like oh no, the beef jerky parade is now marching down street every time--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: What was it, the vegetarian cake.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Vegan cupcake.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: I really shouldn't.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You know what Trump calls comfort food. Food. That's all he eats. And that's why they're all going to lose.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Does this even help any of them?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Marianne Williamson saying that she doesn't have comfort food. I've evolved to be on that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. She eats spirit food.

utterances.speaker: KENNEDY
utterances.utterance: I'm on an air diet. I just breathe.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: All right, you guys. Fan Mail Friday is up next.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You guys.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That is music.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's not music.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No, that's music from the chase scene from the original Planet of the Apes. When Chuck Heston is running from the gorilla.

utterances.speaker: MONTGOMERY
utterances.utterance: Chuck.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Chuck.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You know him as Chuck.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The late Chuck. All right. Fan Mail Friday. That's a good question. What is something you like to do that other people would consider weird if they knew. Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'm not going to tell you. Definitely not telling you.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Something weird.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Something weird. I mean I'm not a weird guy. I think everything I do is pretty normal. I think you're the weird one.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, I'm the weirdo. That's right. Whatever this would probably be considered normal. Like I usually bathe daily. That's weird, right.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, you take a bath or a shower.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I shower.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: OK.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I shower like in a bathtub.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You strike me as a bath guy.

utterances.speaker: SCHOEN
utterances.utterance: I like to watch Democratic speeches for this crowd. That's weird.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That is weird. You're going to have a lot of fun next week.
